I often think that Millennials might be the last generation capable of purely appreciating art and connecting with artists. They don't have that pressure to scrutinize everything through a critical lens.
We grew up during the golden age of media, when people shared a common understanding of pop culture, but today, that collective awareness has disappeared.
At that time, we could directly immerse ourselves without worrying about the source of the content, because tracing origins was not easy in those days.
We revered these artists almost as deities, and there was no reason to question this worship. Thus, we formed a "pseudo-social relationship" with them and regarded it as an essential part of our lives.
This also explains why we are so obsessed with nostalgia.
When the show "The Office" was still on air, my friends and I would gather every Thursday to watch it together while eating pizza.
This is vastly different from our current experience of watching shows through streaming platforms. Streaming services usually release all 12 episodes at once, and everyone watches them at their own pace, adding "spoiler alerts" when posting about the plot on social media, or simply communicating within specific groups.
Unconsciously, we all long to relive that sense of collective belonging that connected everyone.
It is precisely this nostalgia that drives us to rewatch shows like "The Office" or movies like "The Daily Show," whose unforgettable lines spread online like memes.
We would quote these classic lines from the works and assume that most people would understand them.
Nowadays, even if something goes viral online, we can no longer assume everyone has seen it.
Nowadays, with information exploding around us, there's just too much for us to pay attention to, making it impossible to simplify... Do we still have a chance to escape from this state of information overload?
We keep discovering new media and new artists, only to find them either notorious sexual predators or stubborn bigots filled with prejudice, and this cycle repeats itself, growing tiresome.
We are caught in a contradiction: on one hand, we indulge in nostalgia, yet on the other, we must acknowledge that the creators of the art we love may have serious moral flaws, leaving us feeling helpless and conflicted.
We will be more cautious in forming "pseudo-social relationships" with artists.
We gradually realize that if a person wants to gain wealth and power, it becomes difficult to ensure they won't hurt or exploit others.
With the collective consciousness of media no longer present, we have developed a class consciousness that helps us maintain critical thinking.
Of course, there are also some people who still remain stubbornly convinced, insisting on elevating others to a pedestal, only to feign shock when their idols eventually fall.
We are living in an era of transformation, and I urgently want to know where we are heading.
Inclusion and safety should be the default.
